Public procurement of construction services and prevention of corruption
Joint report by the Supreme Control Board of the Czech Republic (NKcomo) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel examinations
Introduction and overview
The awarding of services by public authorities is of great importance both for the state and for the economy.
The task of the state is to use public funds as economically and sparingly as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the awarding of services by public authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.
In order to ensure largely unlimited competition across borders, the contracting authorities must comply with certain EU values (thresholds) in their alloyment of certain value limits (thresholds).
To this end, EU member states must transfer and apply EU procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Below the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate public procurement themselves.
The awarding of benefits is also an area at risk of corruption.
Due to the generally high potential for damage, the contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and inadmissible advantages in awarding their contracts.
In January 2011, the Supreme Control Board of the Czech Republic (NKcomo) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed in January 2011 to carry out parallel audits on both EU-wide allocation of construction services and the prevention of corruption.
The examinations focused on the application of EU procurement law, which is transferred to national rules, as well as the prevention of corruption in the allocation of construction services in construction and road construction or transport infrastructure.
The awards below the EU thresholds were also included in the considerations with regard to corruption prevention.
The audit results of both Court of Auditors are summarised in this Joint Report.
The report is also intended to address international bodies â€“ such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Authorities (INTOSAI).
Audit areas and audited bodies The evaluations of the Federal Audit Office on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional examinations carried out in 201201EB14 2012 at the building authorities responsible for the road and construction of the Federal authorities in Germany.
For example, he examined the construction of motorways as well as large-scale construction projects.
In addition, the Federal Audit Office used results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Control Board of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit skills from 2008 to 2011. The tests included construction work in road construction, rail transport, water construction, construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) as well as other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the awarding of the federal government public contracts is predominantly carried out by the building administrations of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the State Building Administration is centrally responsible for transport infrastructure awards.
In construction, the awarding is carried out in a decentralised manner by those which use state budgets.
In both countries, freelancers are also involved in parts of the procurement procedures.
When comparing the evaluations, differences in procurement law and market structure for construction services in both countries must be taken into account.
Building procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures limited to the national area are governed by budgetary law and the administrative rules based on it.
Both EU-wide and national procurement, many complementary individual arrangements are laid down by intra-administrative provisions,
For example, the so-called "procurement manuals" of the federal government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or formulated in more detail in compliance with the law on procurement law.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed solely by the procurement law and other legal provisions applicable to both the area above and below the EU thresholds.
The law on procurement was significantly amended in 2012.
The new regulation strengthened transparency in the use of public funds, allowed for increased competition and limited the possibilities for corruption in the procurement process.
Broad guidelines of procurement law in both countries
In both countries, EU-wide awards in particular involve the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiation procedure.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold are used by national categories of procurement (public tendering, limited tendering, free-handed procurement), but which are broadly in line with the aforementioned EU-wide procurement types.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the primacy of the open procedure (for contracts to be carried out across the EU) and public tendering (for national awards).
In the open procedure and in the public tender, any interested company can submit an offer.
Another key feature of German procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized enterprises.
The main purpose of this is to divide an overall construction project into skilled and partial loose.
The individual awarding of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the above features of German public procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.
More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are employed in Germany.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures must also be applied to construction projects below the EU threshold.
An exception here is the simplified procedure, in which a less stringent procedure may be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech public procurement law contains provisions, in accordance with EU law, to conclude contracts when competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.
The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow the issuing authorities to choose between the open and the unopen procedure.
There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 are employed by 20 or more.
