The foundations of EU procurement law and prevention of corruption
EU procurement law
In order to ensure unlimited competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the procurement and the Appeals Directive which had to be transposed into national law by the Member States 8.
The general procurement principles of the European Union are, in particular, the requirement for competition, the requirement of equal treatment or the prohibition of discrimination and the transparency requirement.
In order to achieve these objectives, the Procurement Directive contains specific rules for EU-wide construction services for construction projects.
In order to achieve this, their projected order amounts must reach or exceed the current level of 5.000.000.
The rules relate in particular to the content of the procurement documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the adherence to deadlines, including for receipt of the offers, the documentation of the procurement procedure, the requirements The right to be placed on the qualifications of the candidates and the Appeals Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of candidates and bidders.
In the event of possible breaches of public procurement law, affected companies may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in verification proceedings.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the directives of the European Union into national law.
Anti-corruption prevention
Importance of corruption prevention
In both countries, there is no legal definition of the concept of corruption.
In general, corruption is the abuse of a trust for private gain,
Is usually prompted by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hamper competition and result in significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of the world's economic output.
For the European Union, the size of these costs is estimated at 1%.
In the case of public authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair behaviour can call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the basic tasks of public authorities.
In doing so, they must check the establishment and drainage organisation of their administrations for areas that are particularly at risk of corruption in order to take appropriate safeguards against corruption.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly limit the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.
The awarding of public works is, in principle, regarded as a field of work that is particularly at risk of corruption.
Anti-corruption measures
In Germany, corruption â€“ in particular bribery and bribery, as well as acceptance and authorization-is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
To prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a directive and recommendations on corruption prevention in the federal administration. In addition to risk analysis, the following principles must be observed in the procurement area in particular: Priority of public tenders and open procedures, multi-eye principles and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, awarding and billing, accuracy And full documentation of procurement procedures.
In addition, further anti-corruption requirements have been incorporated into the provisions of the law on procurement law.
In 2011, for example, the competent Federal Ministry of Forever of Forgiving in the area of the Federal Highway introduced an electronically supported control system,
With the award data-such as the estimated costs and the order totals-as well as information on the freelance professionals involved, are collected across the board and evaluated for abnormalities.
In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
The legally prescribed precepts of transparency and equal treatment of bidders, as well as the prohibition of all discrimination, form the most important basis of the prevention of corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper to combat corruption for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.
Some of the measures recommended therein have already been transposed into national procurement law and relevant administrative regulations.
The new legislation essentially includes the following provisions: Reduction of the thresholds for smaller contracts, obligation to pre-announce the awarding by the awarding authority, including citing the grounds for tendering, prohibiting the restriction of the Number of bidders in non-open proceedings and thus abolition of the possibility of bidder selection through batch procedures, introduction of the obligation to publish the order documents and all annexes, the introduction of the obligation to publish the Actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Exam results on the individual phases of the procurement process
Procurement documents
Procurement documents The procurement documents must contain all the information that bidders need to make an appropriate bid.
In particular, the procurement documents must allow for an accurate calculation.
Bidders must not be given risks that cannot be calculated for them.
The procurement documents consist in particular of the terms of the service and the terms of the contract.
They also contain the requirements for proving the qualifications (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria that are decisive for the selection of the most economical offer.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
The requirements of EU law on procurement documents are based in particular on the technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should limit competition as little as possible.
The performance description must be product neutral in principle.
Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under narrow conditions.
Avoiding competition-limiting requirements in procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.
In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the procurement documents must be avoided, since it opens up scope for speculation in the creation of the bids and for manipulations in their evaluation.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Similar or similar regulations In both countries, EU legal requirements on technical specifications have been transposed into national law.
The services must in principle be advertisement in a product-neutral manner without factory specifications.
In the performance descriptions, the individual services must normally be divided into performance units with respective quantity data in detail.
Prices are to be agreed on the basis of unit services (e.g. euros per m Â² or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases can services be defined by functional targets.
The performance descriptions must in any case be complete and unambiguous.
They must contain precise quantities and must not include services that do not determine whether they are needed.
Remunerations by lump sum or after time must be avoided as far as possible.
These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indefinite requirements in the procurement documents.
Performance descriptions must allow bidders to create their offerings safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The call for tenders is not to be made known until the award documents have been finalised.
Different regulations
There is no obligation to tender for construction services in lots in the Czech Republic.
If it is possible according to the type of service to be carried, the public procurement agencies can divide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, construction services are generally divided into lots, separated by quantity (partial) and/or by type or subject (skilled).
The aim is to enable medium-sized companies to participate in the competition, to expand the number of possible suppliers and to make price fixing more difficult.
This type of award is considered to be the most economical in terms of the rule.
Valuation criteria must be set out in procurement documents in the Czech Republic for both EU-wide and national procedures.
This should make it fully and conclusively clear to candidates what criteria their offers are to be evaluated.
In Germany, the indication of evaluation criteria in EU-wide announcements, but no later than in the procurement documents, is only mandatory in the EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria must only be recorded in an internal marketing note under administrative control.
Procurement documents prepared by commissioned freelancers may not contain any references to these offices or involved planners or reviewers in Germany to the construction and some road construction administrations.
This is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the client's knowledge through contact with these freelancers.
This is also the reason why freelance professionals are not allowed to send or interpret planning documents for inspection.
The contact person of the companies is the sole client.
There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic.
Additional or amended services, which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements), almost always apply to large construction projects.
In both countries, the statutory provisions allow, to some extent, the award of submissions to the already contracted company, without the possibility of a procurement procedure with public notice.
According to EU regulations and German regulations, the remuneration of the supplementary benefits must not exceed half of the main order.
In addition, the additional services must not be separated from the main order without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a narrower 20% limit applies to allocation without public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.
If additional services are also transferred to the already contracted company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is not possible in principle, according to the regulations in Germany.
On the contrary, in determining the remuneration for the additional services, it must be assumed that the agreed prices and the basis for the price assessment of the order already granted must be based.
In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.
In the Czech Republic, underquantities cannot be offset against additional supplementary benefits.
