Summary findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly in line in both countries and take EU requirements into account.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and prevention of corruption.
For example, the requirement for the sufficient accuracy of performance descriptions should allow bidders to properly calculate and create their offers,
Protect the client from additional services to be agreed afterwards and also curb speculative leeway.
The common basic requirements for procurement documents are supplemented in Germany by regulations aimed at further reducing restrictions on competition and manipulation.
There are no provisions on this scale in the Czech Republic, but transparency is increased by publishing the evaluation criteria in the non-EU-wide procurement procedures.
Performance description requirements have largely been met in both countries.
In some cases, however, there have been complaints of deviations, which may also have led to restrictions on competition.
The requirement for the formation of lots in Germany promotes competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the examination findings of the NKcomo, the awarding of extensive services without lots or with only very large lots can result in restrictions on the provider field on only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements set out in the Czech Republic in road construction have meant that public contracts are awarded only to a narrow group of suppliers and that small and medium-sized enterprises do not participate in the competition. Is made possible.
Also, a limited number of competitors often lead to higher prices and increase the risk of price or other arrangements.
When awarding and remuneration additional or amended benefits, the regulatory approaches differ from one another in both countries.
According to EU regulations and German regulations, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the main order can be awarded under certain conditions without the award procedure with public notice.
In the Czech Republic, there is a narrower limit of 20%, until additional services in the negotiation process can be awarded to the original contractor without notice.
