Europe-wide procurement procedures must be applied to construction projects where an EU-set threshold is reached or exceeded.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
When choosing the type of award, the contracting authority must take into account, in particular, the European law's rights to compete and transparency.
If the estimated total contract value of the construction services of a project is in or above the EU threshold of currently 5.000.000 EUR, the construction services must in principle be allocated throughout Europe in accordance with open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
In the case of construction projects that reach or exceed the EU threshold, the contracting authority may deviate to a limited extent from the principle of Europe-wide procurement and allocate construction services in national procurement, provided that the estimated Order value of the respective lot is below 1.000.000 euros and the sum of these lots does not exceed 20% of the estimated total order value of all construction orders.
A uniform construction project must not be divided into individual measures for no reason or deliberately valued at too low cost values in order to remove it from the obligation to allocate the construction services in principle across Europe.
Since restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of the type of procurement is of great importance in the prevention of corruption.
The in-depth justification of the chosen type of procurement as well as the examination of the application obligation of the EU procurement rules are important components of the documentation of the procurement procedure.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Same or similar regulations
Both countries have fully transposed EU legal requirements on procurement procedures and the threshold into national law.
Different regulations
The Czech Republic has also transferred the fundamental equality of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU Directive to its construction awards, which are not subject to EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open and the non-open procedure, without the decision being dokued or justified. Other procedures, on the other hand, are only possible according to certain conditions defined by law.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure or â€“ of national awards-the public tender is fundamentally a priority. This is determined by budgetary and procurement law and by the directives on preventing corruption.
Other types of procurement â€“ as well as the non-open procedure or the limited tender-are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated under procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be substantiated and documented in a comprehensible manner.
The principle of the primacy of open procedure or public tendering is intended to ensure as unlimited competition as possible, to exclude the possibility of manipulation by specifying certain bidders and to avoid possible price fixing among the Complicate bidders.
The principle of public tendering is a central element of the prevention of corruption in Germany.
The accurate estimation of the expected value of the order is an essential basis in the choice of the correct type of contract.
Construction services in Germany can draw on planning and cost databases of public administrations and other organisations to determine the projected costs of public construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. The databases contain, among other things, cost indicators for building categories, usage units, components or individual construction services.
Based on such cost indicators, the expected order value of a planned pre-life or a construction service to be allocated can be determined.
Corresponding cost databases for road construction have only a few construction administrations in Germany.
However, a nationwide introduction for all road construction administrations is planned.
Procurement agencies in the Czech Republic cannot rely on central databases or average price assessments of comparable construction measures to determine the likely cost of construction services.
On the contrary, the cost investigations are, in most cases, based on estimates of the financing body or from the amount of funds made available to the construction service.
Measures to standardise cost assessment procedures are still in their infancy.
The relevant ministries were commissioned to create a database for standardised building materials and materials as part of the Anti-Corruption Plan for 2011-2012.
