Summary findings
The rules for the examination and evaluation of the offers in both countries are in line with the EU's requirements.
However, in the case of details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the respective rules differ from each other.
In Germany, the procedure is more regulated than in the Czech Republic by detailed requirements, in particular for the implementation of the multi-eye principle and for the protection of offers.
The same applies to the requirements on the basis of which the adequacy of the prices offered must be examined.
In both countries, some of the audited procurement procedures found that substantial procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of bids were not or only inadequately documented.
Without traceability and transparency of the audit and evaluation decisions, however, possible manipulative interventions are encouraged.
A particularly serious deficiency was the handover of all offers to third parties, without the contracting authority having checked and documented the offers sufficiently beforehand and thus protecting them from possible manipulation in the further proceedings.
If public authorities have tasks carried out in the examination and evaluation of the offers by third parties, sufficient precautions and an increased amount of control are required to countering the increased risk of manipulation.
When assessing the adequacy of the prices, the audited services in Germany did not always make full use of the specified set of instruments, inadequately examining the price structure of the offers.
In the Czech Republic, complaints arose mainly in the aptitude test and in the application of the evaluation criteria.
Completion of the procurement procedure
After the examination and values of the offers, the procurement procedure is concluded by issuing the award or by cancelling the procedure.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
In the case of EU-wide procurement procedures, all bidders must be informed in advance of the proposed award decision.
Companies have the option of examining the intended allocation in the event of an electronic notification or by fax within 10 days or in the case of other means of communication within 15 days and, if necessary, initiating an inspection procedure.
A contract may not be concluded before this information period expires.
