If a bidder submits a request for examination within the information period, a conclusion of the contract is only possible after the final decision in the examination procedure.
Companies may also have the procurement decision reviewed by an independent court in the context of this review process.
The verification procedure is intended to ensure the legal protection of the companies and to encourage the client to comply with the law of the contract throughout the procurement process.
To do so, he must sufficiently document the procedure.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Same or similar regulations
Both countries have implemented EU rules on information and verification procedures.
In both countries, the issuing authority has to decide on the award of the contract.
However, it must not deviate arbitrarily from the result of proper examination and evaluation of the offers.
The client is to place the order within the announced surcharge period,
Also because the bidders are no longer bound by their bids after the deadline.
In the case of open and non-open proceedings or public and limited tenders, the client may not deviate from the content of the offer at the time of conclusion of the contract.
The losing bidders must be informed in a timely manner about the award decision and the reasons for not taking into account their offers.
Procurement procedures may only be cancelled under certain conditions, for example if the offer prices are inflated or the offers do not meet the requirements of the tender.
Different regulations
In the Czech Republic, the 10 or 15-day information and waiting obligation before the award of the contract is also subject to the construction services not to be allocated throughout Europe.
In Germany, these requirements apply only to EU-wide awards.
In the case of the other proceedings in Germany, bidders cannot be informed of the award decision until the award has been awarded.
In the Czech Republic, a procurement procedure must be set aside if only one offer has been received or only one offer has been counted.
In Germany, the contract must also be awarded in the case of only one valuable offer, provided that it complies with the terms of the tender and is economical.
