Documentation, reporting and reporting requirements
The procurement procedures must be documented in a comprehensible manner during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings and the justifications of the individual decisions.
In the case of EU-wide procedures, the orders granted must be made known.
Order data is also recorded in an EU statistic.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption By documenting procurement procedures, a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement is implemented.
Carefully and promptly produced documentation only makes it possible to understand the procurement decisions.
In particular, it also serves to provide bidders with effective legal protection in the case of procurement above the EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the compulsion to substantiate procurement decisions in detail significantly narrows the scope for manipulation.
The notice of a given contract at an EU-wide procurement procedure must be submitted to the EU Office of Official Publications within 48 days.
The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU and thus also implements the transparency requirement.
The awarding authorities must also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the EU Commission through the relevant national ministries.
On this basis, the EU Commission produces an annual EU statistic to provide it with an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Same or similar regulations
Both countries have fully transposed EU legal requirements for documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.
Different regulations
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts placed is not limited to EU-wide awards, but also extends to the other procurement procedures.
The notice period is reduced to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to EU-wide awards, there is only a requirement for publication in the case of limited tenders and free-handed awards from the value limits of 25,000 euros or 15,000 euros excluding sales tax (so-called ex-post transparency).
Below these value limits as well as in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition procedure receive information about the order allocations.
