Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits of the NKcomo and the BRH have focused on two areas that are essential for the awarding of construction services by public authorities in the Czech Republic and Germany: The application of EU procurement rules and the Anti-corruption prevention.
The requirements of EU law allow cross-border competition to create a European single market.
Anti-corruption measures do not only serve to avoid or at least reduce corruption. They are also intended to avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit knowledge of the two Court of Auditors on the application of procurement legislation in both countries and the comparison of these rules reveal the similarities and differences that have been made for both countries in the further development of their Procurement law and its application can be helpful.
Application of EU procurement rules
The EU's rules on the awarding of construction services have transposed both countries into national law.
In this way, there is an important common basis in the Czech Republic and Germany for the allocation of construction services and the consideration of the essential commandments of competition, equal treatment of the companies involved and transparency. The procurement procedure.
Some of the building administrations of both countries have underpelled these commandments very extensively by further administrative regulations.
The Czech Republic has largely also transferred the requirements for EU-wide construction services to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the studies carried out by the Court of Auditors have shown that the building authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The construction administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to remedy the complaints identified when implementing the EU requirements.
The audits in the Czech Republic have highlighted, above all, risks affecting the economic viability of the awards.
For example, incomplete performance descriptions necessitated additional services, often awarded in violation of legislation. In addition, the cost investigations were usually inadequately prepared. Excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of possible bidders and restricted competition, particularly in the case of transport buildings.
Anti-corruption prevention
The investigations have not been aimed at detecting corruption cases,
It is also because the Court of Auditors do not have the appropriate instruments for this purpose.
However, the Court of Auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the allocation of construction services and how these requirements are applied.
Both countries have set different priorities in the prevention of corruption.
Above all, the German regulations provide for largely unlimited competition and transparency and controls as central elements of the prevention of corruption.
The Czech rules are aimed primarily at increasing the transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of anti-corruption, which the entire federal administration has to apply, apply.
These principles are also implemented in the requirements for the allocation of construction services and are geared towards their specific requirements.
Some of the relevant rules specify very precisely how the anti-corruption bids should be taken into account in the course of the procurement procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.
In the BRH's view, the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tendering is an appropriate instrument for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in the allocation of construction services. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative interference.
Risk analyses and adequate controls (in particular the multi-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures, as well as various organisational measures are also effective measures to address corruption and Prevent manipulation.
The BRH therefore does not see any fundamental need for change to the relevant requirements of the administrations when awarding construction services.
The rules on the prevention of corruption are largely taken into account in practice.
The deficiencies identified in some areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some requirements.
Building administrations should continue to train their staff on the corruption prevention requirements and raise awareness of this issue.
A significant part of the complaints related to tasks that the building authorities had delegated to freelancers.
However, without controls and adequate safeguards, delegating tasks increases the risk of abuse.
Tasks at risk of manipulation and corruption should therefore only be entrusted to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against undue interference.
