Recommendations
In principle, the NKcomo and the BRH take a positive view of the implementation of the EU's requirements.
The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU's commandments of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for awarding construction services within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and idealistic potential for damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the awarding of construction services, both Court of Auditors see the building authorities in their countries as called upon to continue their measures against corruption and manipulation. And, if necessary, to improve.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously investigated for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to be able to take appropriate countermeasures.
Comparing procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures provide a wider area for competition and can significantly mitigate the risk of corruption.
It can also have a positive impact on supply prices if construction services are shared more favourably in lots, provided that this leads to greater competition with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring the correct implementation of the procurement procedures is an essential basis for the efficient procurement of public contracting.
In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the construction administrations specialising in this. In the Czech Republic, on the other hand, these tasks carry out â€“ with the exception of the transport construction projects â€“ the departments themselves or contractors contracted by them.
The Court of Auditors of both countries are anxious, even after the completion of their joint project, to further develop the knowledge that is important to them and, if necessary, to bring them to the parliament and government of their country.
Both Court of Auditors also believe that the principles of public procurement law and its implementation set out in this report are also of interest at the international level of the International Organization of Supreme Audit Authorities (INTOSAI). The principles and findings set out are of general importance in order to effectively counter corruption and to ensure the economic allocation of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
